nBoth of these already used `<=`, so `getInvoicesByDateRange` was the only inconsistent query. The fix brings it in line. Good.\n\n**LOW -- No index on `date` column.** Looking at `/workspace/src/db/connection.ts`, the `invoices` table has no index on the `date` column. The `<=` vs `<` change does not affect this, but range queries on `date` will perform a full table scan. For a production microservice, consider adding:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_invoices_date ON invoices(date);\n```\n\nThis is pre-existing and not introduced by this diff, so it is out-of-scope for this review but worth noting.\n\n---\n\n### Fix 3: UTC month grouping (`/workspace/src/services/reporting.ts`, line 28)\n\n**Verdict: Correct.**\n\nThe date is constructed with explicit UTC midnight on line 27:\n\n```typescript\nconst d = new Date(inv.date + 'T00:00:00Z');\n```\n\nUsing `getMonth()` (local time) on a UTC-midnight date would shift the date backward in negative-UTC-offset timezones (e.g., `America/New_York` at UTC-5), causing `2024-03-01T00:00:00Z` to appear as February 29th in local time, and `getMonth()` would return `1` (February) instead of `2` (March). The fix to `getUTCMonth()` is correct and matches the rest of the UTC-aware date handling in `/workspace/src/utils/dates.ts`.\n\nThe test suite explicitly sets `process.env.TZ = 'America/New_York'` at the top of both test files, which means the regression test `'month boundary grouping assigns first day to correct month'` (regression.test.ts, line 42) would have failed with the old `getMonth()` code. This is excellent test design.\n\n**LOW -- `getUTCDate()` not needed elsewhere but worth auditing.** The `formatDate` utility in `/workspace/src/utils/dates.ts` already uses `getUTCFullYear()`, `getUTCMonth()`, and `getUTCDate()` consistently (lines 7-9). The `TODO: fix timezone` comment on line 5 of that file appears to be stale, since the function already uses UTC methods correctly. Consider removing that TODO to avoid confu